The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, January 28, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, Jan. 27: The government is likely to further simplify import and export rules on Wednesday even as it has decided to leave it to the new government to present a full-fledged exim policy. Commerce minister Arun Jaitley, who will launch digital signature and electronic fund transfer facility, may announce a simplification of procedures.																								 New Delhi, Jan. 27: Air Sahara today launched four coupon square drive economy class and super four business class ticket options priced at Rs 24,000 and Rs 32,000, respectively. These have a validity of 90 days. It has reintroduced the sixer and super sixer ticket options at Rs 33,000 and Rs 43,500, respectively, with a validity of 120 days.																								 Calcutta, Jan. 27: Indal, a subsidiary of Hindalco Industries, has extended the buyback offer to shareholders till February 2005. Company sources said the offer would be priced at Rs 120 per share and available to shareholders who could not participate in the earlier exit option.																								 New Delhi, Jan. 27: The Centre is expected to end this fiscal with a shortfall of about Rs 5,000 crore in indirect tax collections targeted at Rs 1,45,476 crore. However, a buoyant direct tax mopup may compensate the shortfall partially and result in lower fiscal deficit, finance ministry officials said.																								 New Delhi, Jan. 27: Association of Basic Telecom Operators (ABTO) is considering changing its name to Association of Unified Telecom Service providers.
